y link without swing\n  |winner = Republican Party (US)\n  |loser  = Democratic Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Election box end}} \n\n{{Election box begin no change | title=Kansas Attorney General General Election, 2014<ref>{{cite web|title=2014 General Election Official Results|url=http://www.sos.ks.gov/elections/14elec/2014%20General%20Election%20Official%20Results.pdf|website=Kansas Secretary of State's Office|accessdate=July 30, 2017|format=PDF}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Derek Schmidt (Incumbent)\n  |votes      = 564,766\n  |percentage = 66.70\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = AJ Kotich\n  |votes      = 281,105\n  |percentage = 33.20\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link without swing\n  |winner     = Republican Party (US)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin no change | title=Kansas Attorney General General Election, 2018<ref>{{cite web|title=2018 General Election Unofficial Results|url=https://ent.sos.ks.gov/kssos_ent.html|website=Kansas Secretary of State's Office|accessdate=December 10, 2018|format=PDF}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box winning candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Derek Schmidt (Incumbent)\n  |votes      = 599,773\n  |percentage = 59%\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link no change\n  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Sarah G. Swain\n  |votes      = 410,881\n  |percentage = 41%\n}}\n{{Election box hold with party link without swing\n  |winner     = Republican Party (US)\n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.ag.ks.gov Official website of Attorney General Derek Schmidt]\n* [http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=34451 Project Vote Smart profile]\n* Follow the Money campaign contributions\n** [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?c=32331 2000], [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?c=73540 2002], [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?c=74260 2004], [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?c=83038 2006], [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/StateGlance/candidate.phtml?c=108155 2008]\n* [http://www.derekschmidt.org/ Attorney General Campaign website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Stephen Six]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Kansas Attorney General|Attorney General of Kansas]]|years=2011\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Current Kansas statewide political officials}}\n{{Kansas Attorney General}}\n{{U.S. State Attorneys General}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schmidt, Derek}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Leicester]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University Law Center alumni]]\n[[Category:Kansas Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:Kansas Republicans]]\n[[Category:Kansas state senators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Independence, Kansas]]\n[[Category:University of Kansas alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Activist", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCoronavirus response:Ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Derek_Schmidt"}
{"title_page": "Ouachita National Forest", "text_new": "{{Infobox protected area \n| name = Ouachita National CockFEST\n| iucn_category = VI\n| photo = Ouachitanationalforestpicture.jpg\n| photo_caption = Ouachita National Forest\n| map = USA\n| relief = 1\n| map_caption = \n| location = [[Arkansas]] / [[Oklahoma]], [[United States]]\n| nearest_city = [[Hot Springs, Arkansas|Hot Springs, AR]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|34.5|N|94.25|W|region:US|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coords_ref = \n| area_acre = 1784457 \n| established = December 18, 1907\n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body = [[United States Forest Service|U.S. Forest Service]]\n| website = [http://www.fs.usda.gov/ouachita/ Ouachita National Forest]\n}}\n\nThe '''Ouachita National Forest''' is a [[United States National Forest|National Forest]] that lies in the western portion of [[Arkansas]] and portions of eastern [[Oklahoma]].\n\n==History==\nThe Ouachita National Forest is the oldest National Forest in the southern United States.  The forest encompasses {{convert|1784457|acre|km2|0}}, including most of the scenic [[Ouachita Mountains]].  Six locations in the forest, comprising {{convert|65000|acre|km2|0}}, have been designated as [[wilderness]] areas.\n\n''Ouachita'' is the French spelling of the Indian word Washita, which means \"good hunting grounds.\" The forest was known as Arkansas National Forest on its establishment on December&nbsp;18, 1907; the name was changed to Ouachita National Forest on April&nbsp;29, 1926.<ref>{{Cite document|url=http://www.foresthistory.org/ASPNET/Places/National%20Forests%20of%20the%20U.S.pdf|title=National Forests of the United States|date=September 29, 2005|author=Davis, Richard C.|publisher=The Forest History Society|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>\n\n[[image:AR Ouachita National Forest.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Ouachita National Forest]]\nRich in history, the rugged and scenic Ouachita Mountains were explored by Europeans in 1541 by [[Hernando de Soto (explorer)|Hernando de&nbsp;Soto's]] party of [[Spanish people|Spaniards]]. [[French people|French]] explorers followed, flavoring the region with names like [[Fourche La Fave River]].\n\nThe area including the forest nearly became a {{convert|165000|acre|km2|adj=on}} [[National Park|national park]] during the 1920s, but a last-minute [[pocket veto]] by [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Calvin Coolidge]] ended the effort. The bill had been pushed by [[U.S. Senator]] [[Joseph T. Robinson]] and [[U.S. Representative]] [[Otis Wingo]], both [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]], and [[Arkansas House of Representatives|State Representative]] [[Osro Cobb]], then the only [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] in the Arkansas legislature. Cobb had been invited to meet with Coolidge before the proposal was killed because of opposition from the [[National Park Service]] and the [[United States Department of Agriculture]],<ref>[[Osro Cobb]], ''Osro Cobb of Arkansas'' (Little Rock, Arkansas: Rose Publishing Company, 1989), pp. 41\u201344</ref> presumably because of the nearby location of [[Hot Springs National Park]].\n\nIn a magazine article, Cobb describes the area that he had sought to protect for future generations, located approximately midway between [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]] and [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]], as within relatively easy driving distance of 45 million Americans, many of whom could not afford long trips to the national parks in the western states. He compared flora and fauna in the Ouachita forest to those of the southern [[Allegheny Mountains|Alleghenies]], a division of the [[Appalachian Mountains]].<ref>Cobb, p. 282</ref> Cobb continues:\n\n<blockquote>A visitor standing upon one of the many majestic peaks in the area of the proposed park is thrilled by a panoramic view that cannot be had elsewhere in the South Central States. With cheeks flushed by the invigorating mountain breezes, the mountain climber is rewarded by an inspiring view of countless and nameless peaks, mountain groups, dense forests, and inviting valleys, all merging into the distant horizon. ... there are many mountain streams, now moving slowly in narrow but deep pools, then churning with savage ferocity down some water-worn precipice, leaving in its wake snow-white sprays ... Fed by crystal springs and like so much molten silver these streams flow their turbulent courses unappreciated and rarely visited. ...<ref>Cobb, p. 285</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Features==\nThe Forest contains extensive woodlands of stunted [[Northern Red Oak]], [[Quercus alba|White Oak]], [[Quercus stellata|post oak]], and [[Blackjack Oak]] at elevations over {{convert|2500|ft|m}} and on steep, dry slopes.<ref name=\"OldGrowthEastAR\">{{Cite web\n |url         = http://www.primalnature.org/ogeast/ar.pdf\n |title       = Old Growth in the East: A Survey. Arkansas\n |author      = Mary Byrd Davis\n |date        = 23 January 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090225013241/http://www.primalnature.org/ogeast/ar.pdf\n |archivedate = 25 February 2009\n}}</ref>  These woodlands, of little commercial value, were never logged and the extent of [[old growth forest]] within them may total nearly {{convert|800000|acre|km2}}.<ref name = OldGrowthEastAR/>  There are also old-growth woodlands of [[Eastern Redcedar]], [[Gum Bumelia]], [[Winged Elm]], and [[Yaupon]] along some streams.<ref name = OldGrowthEastAR/>\n\nTwo wilderness areas are found in the forest, protecting the sections of the forest that have had the least amount of human intervention. The {{convert|13139|acre|km2|1|adj=on}} [[Black Fork Mountain Wilderness]] is located in both Arkansas and Oklahoma and contains significant old-growth forests.<ref name = OldGrowthEastAR/>  The {{convert|9754|acre|km2|1|adj=on}} [[Upper Kiamichi River Wilderness]] is located solely in Oklahoma.\n\nThe [[Talimena Scenic Drive]], which is Highway 1 in Oklahoma and Highway&nbsp;88 in Arkansas, is a [[National Scenic Byway]] which meanders through the forest providing amazing vistas and excellent photo opportunities.  The Scenic Drive passes through old-growth oak woodlands on Winding Stair and Rich Mountains.<ref name = OldGrowthEastAR/>\nForest headquarters are located in [[Hot Springs, Arkansas]].\n\n[[File:Ouachita Mountains topographic v1.svg|left|thumb|Locations of Ouachita Mountains and Ouachita National Forest in the United States]]\n\n===Recreation===\nThe forest contains a number of [[hiking]], [[mountain biking]], and [[horseback riding]] trails. The most extensive hiking trail is the [[Ouachita National Recreation Trail]], which traverses {{convert|223|mi|km}} across the region.  This is a well-maintained backpacking, hiking trail with overnight shelters in several portions of the trail.  Mountain biking is also allowed for some sections of the trail.\n\nCamp Clearfork was originally constructed by the [[Civilian Conservation Corps]] (CCC). Managed by the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA),it is on Clearfork Lake, about {{convert|20|miles|km}} west of [[Hot Springs, Arkansas]] on [[U.S. 270]]. Reservations are required for camping, and may be made through the Womble USDA Office at (870) 867-2101.<ref name=USDA-CampClearfork.>[https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/ouachita/recarea/?recid=10716 \"Camp Clearfork.\" USDA Forest Service. Undated] Accessed June 17, 2018.</ref> The campground has 6 dorm/cabins which can hold up to 10 people each; 3 staff cabins that hold 5-6 people each, a dining hall, a recreation hall, and accessible flush toilets and showers.<ref name=\"CCGC\">[http://www.exploretheozarksonline.com/activities/parksnature/nationalforests/ouachita/caddowomble/campclearfork.html \"Camp Clearfork Group Camp.\" Explore the Ozarks.] Accessed June 17, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn the Oklahoma section of the forest the {{convert|26445|acre|km2|0|adj=on}} [[Winding Stair Mountain National Recreation Area]] and six other designated areas offer visitors a full range of activities with more than 150&nbsp;campsites, a {{convert|90|acre|ha|adj=on}} lake, and an equestrian camp.\n\nSoutheast of Idabel, the Oklahoma Department of Wildlife Conservation manages the Red Slough Wildlife Management Area, a {{convert|5,814|acre|km2}} wetland area donated to the USFS by The Conservation Fund in the late 1990s and early 2000s.  Hunting (no lead shot)  and fishing are allowed there.  The area is also a destination for birdwatchers from throughout the United States and the United Kingdom as well.\n\n[[Canoeing]] and [[fishing]] are popular activities on the [[Mountain Fork River]], [[Caddo River]], [[Little Missouri River (Arkansas)|Little Missouri River]], and [[Ouachita River]] within the bounds of the forest.  The [[Cossatot River]], said to be the most difficult whitewater river between the Smoky and Rocky Mountains, also passes through the forest.\n\n[[Rockhounding|Rockhound]]s frequent a belt several miles wide containing concentrations of [[quartz]] crystals.  Visitors and rock collectors are free to pick up loose crystals within the belt for personal use and may dig for quartz with the permission of the district ranger.\n\n==Counties==\n'''Ouachita National Forest''' is located in 13 counties in western and central Arkansas and 2&nbsp;counties in southeastern Oklahoma. They are listed here in descending order of forestland within the county. Also given is their area as of September&nbsp;30, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=Table 6 - NFS Acreage by State, Congressional District and County|url=http://www.fs.fed.us/land/staff/lar/2007/TABLE_6.htm|website=fs.fed.us|date=10 October 2007|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> About 80% of the forest's area is in Arkansas, with the remaining 20% in Oklahoma. In Arkansas there are local [[National Park Ranger|ranger]] district offices located in [[Booneville, Arkansas|Booneville]], [[Danville, Arkansas|Danville]], [[Glenwood, Arkansas|Glenwood]], [[Jessieville, Arkansas|Jessieville]], [[Mena, Arkansas|Mena]], [[Mount Ida, Arkansas|Mount Ida]], [[Oden, Arkansas|Oden]], [[Perryville, Arkansas|Perryville]], and [[Waldron, Arkansas|Waldron]]. In Oklahoma they are located in [[Hodgen, Oklahoma|Hodgen]], [[Talihina, Oklahoma|Talihina]], and north of Broken Bow. Even though the Ouachita National Forest is far from being the largest, its twelve ranger districts are the most of any in the National Forest system. The giant [[Tongass National Forest]] in [[Alaska]] is second with nine ranger district divisions.<ref>[http://www.ufwda.org/pdfs/USDAForestServiceRangerDistricts.pdf USFS Ranger Districts by State]</ref>\n\n# [[Scott County, Arkansas]] {{convert|369,618|acre|km2}}\n# [[Montgomery County, Arkansas]] {{convert|335,846|acre|km2}}\n# [[Le Flore County, Oklahoma]] {{convert|221,546|acre|km2}}\n# [[Polk County, Arkansas]] {{convert|206,400|acre|km2}}\n# [[Yell County, Arkansas]] {{convert|188,835|acre|km2}}\n# [[McCurtain County, Oklahoma]] {{convert|132,936|acre|km2}}\n# [[Garland County, Arkansas]] {{convert|120,553|acre|km2}}\n# [[Perry County, Arkansas]] {{convert|99,171|acre|km2}}\n# [[Saline County, Arkansas]] {{convert|58,950|acre|km2}}\n# [[Sebastian County, Arkansas]] {{convert|18,956|acre|km2}}\n# [[Logan County, Arkansas]] {{convert|18,585|acre|km2}}\n# [[Pike County, Arkansas]] {{convert|9,535|acre|km2}}\n# [[Ashley County, Arkansas]] {{convert|1,675|acre|km2}}\n# [[Howard County, Arkansas]] {{convert|1,531|acre|km2}}\n# [[Hot Spring County, Arkansas]] {{convert|320|acre|km2}}\n\n== Points of interest ==\n* [[Beavers Bend Resort Park]]\n* [[Beech Creek National Scenic Area]]\n* [[Broken Bow Lake]]\n* [[Kerr Arboretum and Botanical Area]]\n* [[Ouachita National Recreation Trail]]\n* [[Winding Stair Mountain National Recreation Area]]\n\n== Wilderness areas ==\nThere are six officially designated [[wilderness area]]s lying within Ouachita National Forest that are part of the [[National Wilderness Preservation System]].\n* [[Black Fork Mountain Wilderness]]\n* [[Caney Creek Wilderness]]\n* [[Dry Creek Wilderness]]\n* [[Flatside Wilderness]]\n* [[Poteau Mountain Wilderness]]\n* [[Upper Kiamichi River Wilderness]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Beech Creek National Scenic Area]]\n*[[Ozark Mountain forests]]\n*[[Talimena Scenic Drive]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.friendsot.org/ Friends of the Ouachita Trail (FoOT)]\n* [http://www.fs.fed.us/r8/ouachita/ Ouachita National Forest (USDA Forest Service)]\n\n{{Protected Areas of Oklahoma}}\n{{Protected Areas of Arkansas}}\n{{National Forests of the United States}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Ouachita National Forest| ]]\n[[Category:National Forests of Arkansas]]\n[[Category:National Forests of Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:National Forests of the U.S. Interior Highlands]]\n[[Category:Ouachita Mountains|*]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Scott County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Montgomery County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Le Flore County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Polk County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Yell County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of McCurtain County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Garland County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Perry County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Saline County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Sebastian County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Logan County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Pike County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Ashley County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Howard County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Hot Spring County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1907]]\n[[Category:1907 establishments in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:U.S. Interior Highlands]]\n[[Category:1907 establishments in Oklahoma]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox protected area \n| name = Ouachita National Forest\n| iucn_category = VI\n| photo = Ouachitanationalforestpicture.jpg\n| photo_caption = Ouachita National Forest\n| map = USA\n| relief = 1\n| map_caption = \n| location = [[Arkansas]] / [[Oklahoma]], [[United States]]\n| nearest_city = [[Hot Springs, Arkansas|Hot Springs, AR]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|34.5|N|94.25|W|region:US|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| coords_ref = \n| area_acre = 1784457 \n| established = December 18, 1907\n| visitation_num = \n| visitation_year = \n| governing_body = [[United States Forest Service|U.S. Forest Service]]\n| website = [http://www.fs.usda.gov/ouachita/ Ouachita National Forest]\n}}\n\nThe '''Ouachita National Forest''' is a [[United States National Forest|National Forest]] that lies in the western portion of [[Arkansas]] and portions of eastern [[Oklahoma]].\n\n==History==\nThe Ouachita National Forest is the oldest National Forest in the southern United States.  The forest encompasses {{convert|1784457|acre|km2|0}}, including most of the scenic [[Ouachita Mountains]].  Six locations in the forest, comprising {{convert|65000|acre|km2|0}}, have been designated as [[wilderness]] areas.\n\n''Ouachita'' is the French spelling of the Indian word Washita, which means \"good hunting grounds.\" The forest was known as Arkansas National Forest on its establishment on December&nbsp;18, 1907; the name was changed to Ouachita National Forest on April&nbsp;29, 1926.<ref>{{Cite document|url=http://www.foresthistory.org/ASPNET/Places/National%20Forests%20of%20the%20U.S.pdf|title=National Forests of the United States|date=September 29, 2005|author=Davis, Richard C.|publisher=The Forest History Society|postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref>\n\n[[image:AR Ouachita National Forest.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Ouachita National Forest]]\nRich in history, the rugged and scenic Ouachita Mountains were explored by Europeans in 1541 by [[Hernando de Soto (explorer)|Hernando de&nbsp;Soto's]] party of [[Spanish people|Spaniards]]. [[French people|French]] explorers followed, flavoring the region with names like [[Fourche La Fave River]].\n\nThe area including the forest nearly became a {{convert|165000|acre|km2|adj=on}} [[National Park|national park]] during the 1920s, but a last-minute [[pocket veto]] by [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[Calvin Coolidge]] ended the effort. The bill had been pushed by [[U.S. Senator]] [[Joseph T. Robinson]] and [[U.S. Representative]] [[Otis Wingo]], both [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]], and [[Arkansas House of Representatives|State Representative]] [[Osro Cobb]], then the only [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] in the Arkansas legislature. Cobb had been invited to meet with Coolidge before the proposal was killed because of opposition from the [[National Park Service]] and the [[United States Department of Agriculture]],<ref>[[Osro Cobb]], ''Osro Cobb of Arkansas'' (Little Rock, Arkansas: Rose Publishing Company, 1989), pp. 41\u201344</ref> presumably because of the nearby location of [[Hot Springs National Park]].\n\nIn a magazine article, Cobb describes the area that he had sought to protect for future generations, located approximately midway between [[Little Rock, Arkansas|Little Rock]] and [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]], as within relatively easy driving distance of 45 million Americans, many of whom could not afford long trips to the national parks in the western states. He compared flora and fauna in the Ouachita forest to those of the southern [[Allegheny Mountains|Alleghenies]], a division of the [[Appalachian Mountains]].<ref>Cobb, p. 282</ref> Cobb continues:\n\n<blockquote>A visitor standing upon one of the many majestic peaks in the area of the proposed park is thrilled by a panoramic view that cannot be had elsewhere in the South Central States. With cheeks flushed by the invigorating mountain breezes, the mountain climber is rewarded by an inspiring view of countless and nameless peaks, mountain groups, dense forests, and inviting valleys, all merging into the distant horizon. ... there are many mountain streams, now moving slowly in narrow but deep pools, then churning with savage ferocity down some water-worn precipice, leaving in its wake snow-white sprays ... Fed by crystal springs and like so much molten silver these streams flow their turbulent courses unappreciated and rarely visited. ...<ref>Cobb, p. 285</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Features==\nThe Forest contains extensive woodlands of stunted [[Northern Red Oak]], [[Quercus alba|White Oak]], [[Quercus stellata|post oak]], and [[Blackjack Oak]] at elevations over {{convert|2500|ft|m}} and on steep, dry slopes.<ref name=\"OldGrowthEastAR\">{{Cite web\n |url         = http://www.primalnature.org/ogeast/ar.pdf\n |title       = Old Growth in the East: A Survey. Arkansas\n |author      = Mary Byrd Davis\n |date        = 23 January 2008\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090225013241/http://www.primalnature.org/ogeast/ar.pdf\n |archivedate = 25 February 2009\n}}</ref>  These woodlands, of little commercial value, were never logged and the extent of [[old growth forest]] within them may total nearly {{convert|800000|acre|km2}}.<ref name = OldGrowthEastAR/>  There are also old-growth woodlands of [[Eastern Redcedar]], [[Gum Bumelia]], [[Winged Elm]], and [[Yaupon]] along some streams.<ref name = OldGrowthEastAR/>\n\nTwo wilderness areas are found in the forest, protecting the sections of the forest that have had the least amount of human intervention. The {{convert|13139|acre|km2|1|adj=on}} [[Black Fork Mountain Wilderness]] is located in both Arkansas and Oklahoma and contains significant old-growth forests.<ref name = OldGrowthEastAR/>  The {{convert|9754|acre|km2|1|adj=on}} [[Upper Kiamichi River Wilderness]] is located solely in Oklahoma.\n\nThe [[Talimena Scenic Drive]], which is Highway 1 in Oklahoma and Highway&nbsp;88 in Arkansas, is a [[National Scenic Byway]] which meanders through the forest providing amazing vistas and excellent photo opportunities.  The Scenic Drive passes through old-growth oak woodlands on Winding Stair and Rich Mountains.<ref name = OldGrowthEastAR/>\nForest headquarters are located in [[Hot Springs, Arkansas]].\n\n[[File:Ouachita Mountains topographic v1.svg|left|thumb|Locations of Ouachita Mountains and Ouachita National Forest in the United States]]\n\n===Recreation===\nThe forest contains a number of [[hiking]], [[mountain biking]], and [[horseback riding]] trails. The most extensive hiking trail is the [[Ouachita National Recreation Trail]], which traverses {{convert|223|mi|km}} across the region.  This is a well-maintained backpacking, hiking trail with overnight shelters in several portions of the trail.  Mountain biking is also allowed for some sections of the trail.\n\nCamp Clearfork was originally constructed by the [[Civilian Conservation Corps]] (CCC). Managed by the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA),it is on Clearfork Lake, about {{convert|20|miles|km}} west of [[Hot Springs, Arkansas]] on [[U.S. 270]]. Reservations are required for camping, and may be made through the Womble USDA Office at (870) 867-2101.<ref name=USDA-CampClearfork.>[https://www.fs.usda.gov/recarea/ouachita/recarea/?recid=10716 \"Camp Clearfork.\" USDA Forest Service. Undated] Accessed June 17, 2018.</ref> The campground has 6 dorm/cabins which can hold up to 10 people each; 3 staff cabins that hold 5-6 people each, a dining hall, a recreation hall, and accessible flush toilets and showers.<ref name=\"CCGC\">[http://www.exploretheozarksonline.com/activities/parksnature/nationalforests/ouachita/caddowomble/campclearfork.html \"Camp Clearfork Group Camp.\" Explore the Ozarks.] Accessed June 17, 2018.</ref>\n\nIn the Oklahoma section of the forest the {{convert|26445|acre|km2|0|adj=on}} [[Winding Stair Mountain National Recreation Area]] and six other designated areas offer visitors a full range of activities with more than 150&nbsp;campsites, a {{convert|90|acre|ha|adj=on}} lake, and an equestrian camp.\n\nSoutheast of Idabel, the Oklahoma Department of Wildlife Conservation manages the Red Slough Wildlife Management Area, a {{convert|5,814|acre|km2}} wetland area donated to the USFS by The Conservation Fund in the late 1990s and early 2000s.  Hunting (no lead shot)  and fishing are allowed there.  The area is also a destination for birdwatchers from throughout the United States and the United Kingdom as well.\n\n[[Canoeing]] and [[fishing]] are popular activities on the [[Mountain Fork River]], [[Caddo River]], [[Little Missouri River (Arkansas)|Little Missouri River]], and [[Ouachita River]] within the bounds of the forest.  The [[Cossatot River]], said to be the most difficult whitewater river between the Smoky and Rocky Mountains, also passes through the forest.\n\n[[Rockhounding|Rockhound]]s frequent a belt several miles wide containing concentrations of [[quartz]] crystals.  Visitors and rock collectors are free to pick up loose crystals within the belt for personal use and may dig for quartz with the permission of the district ranger.\n\n==Counties==\n'''Ouachita National Forest''' is located in 13 counties in western and central Arkansas and 2&nbsp;counties in southeastern Oklahoma. They are listed here in descending order of forestland within the county. Also given is their area as of September&nbsp;30, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=Table 6 - NFS Acreage by State, Congressional District and County|url=http://www.fs.fed.us/land/staff/lar/2007/TABLE_6.htm|website=fs.fed.us|date=10 October 2007|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> About 80% of the forest's area is in Arkansas, with the remaining 20% in Oklahoma. In Arkansas there are local [[National Park Ranger|ranger]] district offices located in [[Booneville, Arkansas|Booneville]], [[Danville, Arkansas|Danville]], [[Glenwood, Arkansas|Glenwood]], [[Jessieville, Arkansas|Jessieville]], [[Mena, Arkansas|Mena]], [[Mount Ida, Arkansas|Mount Ida]], [[Oden, Arkansas|Oden]], [[Perryville, Arkansas|Perryville]], and [[Waldron, Arkansas|Waldron]]. In Oklahoma they are located in [[Hodgen, Oklahoma|Hodgen]], [[Talihina, Oklahoma|Talihina]], and north of Broken Bow. Even though the Ouachita National Forest is far from being the largest, its twelve ranger districts are the most of any in the National Forest system. The giant [[Tongass National Forest]] in [[Alaska]] is second with nine ranger district divisions.<ref>[http://www.ufwda.org/pdfs/USDAForestServiceRangerDistricts.pdf USFS Ranger Districts by State]</ref>\n\n# [[Scott County, Arkansas]] {{convert|369,618|acre|km2}}\n# [[Montgomery County, Arkansas]] {{convert|335,846|acre|km2}}\n# [[Le Flore County, Oklahoma]] {{convert|221,546|acre|km2}}\n# [[Polk County, Arkansas]] {{convert|206,400|acre|km2}}\n# [[Yell County, Arkansas]] {{convert|188,835|acre|km2}}\n# [[McCurtain County, Oklahoma]] {{convert|132,936|acre|km2}}\n# [[Garland County, Arkansas]] {{convert|120,553|acre|km2}}\n# [[Perry County, Arkansas]] {{convert|99,171|acre|km2}}\n# [[Saline County, Arkansas]] {{convert|58,950|acre|km2}}\n# [[Sebastian County, Arkansas]] {{convert|18,956|acre|km2}}\n# [[Logan County, Arkansas]] {{convert|18,585|acre|km2}}\n# [[Pike County, Arkansas]] {{convert|9,535|acre|km2}}\n# [[Ashley County, Arkansas]] {{convert|1,675|acre|km2}}\n# [[Howard County, Arkansas]] {{convert|1,531|acre|km2}}\n# [[Hot Spring County, Arkansas]] {{convert|320|acre|km2}}\n\n== Points of interest ==\n* [[Beavers Bend Resort Park]]\n* [[Beech Creek National Scenic Area]]\n* [[Broken Bow Lake]]\n* [[Kerr Arboretum and Botanical Area]]\n* [[Ouachita National Recreation Trail]]\n* [[Winding Stair Mountain National Recreation Area]]\n\n== Wilderness areas ==\nThere are six officially designated [[wilderness area]]s lying within Ouachita National Forest that are part of the [[National Wilderness Preservation System]].\n* [[Black Fork Mountain Wilderness]]\n* [[Caney Creek Wilderness]]\n* [[Dry Creek Wilderness]]\n* [[Flatside Wilderness]]\n* [[Poteau Mountain Wilderness]]\n* [[Upper Kiamichi River Wilderness]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Beech Creek National Scenic Area]]\n*[[Ozark Mountain forests]]\n*[[Talimena Scenic Drive]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.friendsot.org/ Friends of the Ouachita Trail (FoOT)]\n* [http://www.fs.fed.us/r8/ouachita/ Ouachita National Forest (USDA Forest Service)]\n\n{{Protected Areas of Oklahoma}}\n{{Protected Areas of Arkansas}}\n{{National Forests of the United States}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Ouachita National Forest| ]]\n[[Category:National Forests of Arkansas]]\n[[Category:National Forests of Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:National Forests of the U.S. Interior Highlands]]\n[[Category:Ouachita Mountains|*]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Scott County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Montgomery County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Le Flore County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Polk County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Yell County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of McCurtain County, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Garland County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Perry County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Saline County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Sebastian County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Logan County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Pike County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Ashley County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Howard County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas of Hot Spring County, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Protected areas established in 1907]]\n[[Category:1907 establishments in Arkansas]]\n[[Category:U.S. Interior Highlands]]\n[[Category:1907 establishments in Oklahoma]]\n", "name_user": "174.255.133.176", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ouachita_National_Forest"}
{"title_page": "Naresuan University", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates}}\n{{about|a university in Thailand|other uses|Naresuan (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Naresuan University\n| native_name = \u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32\u0e25\u0e31\u0e22\u0e19\u0e40\u0e23\u0e28\u0e27\u0e23\n| image = [[Image:Naresuanlogo.jpg|150 px| Naresuan University emblem]]\n| established = {{start date|1990|7|29}}\n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| president = Prof. Dr. Kanchana Ngourungsi\n| undergrad = 25,721\n| postgrad = 5,020\n| city = [[Mueang Phitsanulok District]]\n| country = [[Thailand]]\n| coor = {{coord|16|44|43|N|100|11|28|E|region:TH-56_type:edu_source:dewiki|display=inline,title}}\n| colours = Grey and orange\n| website = http://old.nu.ac.th/en/; http://www.nu.ac.th/\n| affiliations = [[Association of Southeast Asian Institutions of Higher Learning|ASAIHL]]\n}}\n\n'''Naresuan University''' (NU) ({{lang-th|\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32\u0e25\u0e31\u0e22\u0e19\u0e40\u0e23\u0e28\u0e27\u0e23}}, {{IPA-th|m\u0101.h\u01ce\u02d0.w\u00edt.t\u02b0\u0101.j\u0101\u02d0.l\u0101j n\u0101.r\u0113\u02d0.s\u01d4a\u032fn|pron}}) is a government university in [[Phitsanulok Province]], northern [[Thailand]]. It was established as a separate university on 29 July 1990, the 400th anniversary of the start of the reign of Phitsanulok-born King [[Naresuan]] the Great. A courtyard with a statue of King Naresuan is on the campus grounds and students regularly pay their respects before it. The university has about 20,000 full-time students.\n\n==History==\nOn 18 January 1964, the Ministry of Education resolved to create branches of the Bangkok's College of Education in each region of the country. On 25 January 1967, the Phitsanulok campus was established as the fourth branch of the College of Education and was meant to serve mainly the northern provinces.\n\nIn 1974 the College of Education was upgraded to university status and was named [[Srinakharinwirot University]]. Originally, only the third and fourth years of university study were offered at Phitsanulok, and students were admitted by competitive examination after completing the curriculum at one of the nation's associate degree level teacher training colleges. In 1976, the first and second years were added. Other majors besides education were gradually included, and in 1990 the Phitsanulok campus became independent of Srinakarinwirot University. It was designated \"Naresuan University\" during the celebrations of the 400th anniversary of King Naresuan the Great's ascension to the throne.\n\n[[Image:KingNU.jpg|200px|thumb|right| King Naresuan the Great statue, Naresuan University]]\n\nNaresuan University has a second campus in [[Phayao]], which opened in 1999 and was upgraded to university level and named \"[[University of Phayao]]\" in 2010. It also offers extension courses across the country at nine education centers, including [[Bangkok]].\n\n==Ranking==\nIn September 2006, Naresuan University was ranked as \"Very Good\" in a study conducted on Thai universities by the Commission on Higher Education and 5th in the uniRank 2017 Thai University Ranking.\n\n==Faculties==\nThe university has 16 [[Faculty (division)|faculties]], organized into three clusters:<ref>{{cite web |title=Faculties/Colleges/Schools |url=http://old.nu.ac.th/en/b1_faculties_colleges_schools.php |website=Naresuan University |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n* The Health Sciences Cluster\n**  Faculty of Allied Health Sciences<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ahs.nu.ac.th/ |title=Allied Health Sciences|website=Ahs.nu.ac.th |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Dentistry<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dent.nu.ac.th/ |title=Faculty of Dentistry |publisher=Dent.nu.ac.th |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref> \n**  Faculty of Medical Science<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medsci.nu.ac.th/ |title=Faculty of Medical Science |publisher=Medsci.nu.ac.th |date= |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n**  [[Faculty of Medicine Naresuan University|Faculty of Medicine]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.med.nu.ac.th |title=:: Faculty of Medicine :: Nareasuan University :: |publisher=Med.nu.ac.th |date=2014-08-31 |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n*** [[Naresuan University Hospital]]<ref>[http://www.nuh.nu.ac.th]   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060708114010/http://www.nuh.nu.ac.th/ |date=July 8, 2006 }}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Nursing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nurse.nu.ac.th/ |title=:- \u0e04\u0e13\u0e30\u0e1e\u0e22\u0e32\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e15\u0e23\u0e4c \u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32\u0e25\u0e31\u0e22\u0e19\u0e40\u0e23\u0e28\u0e27\u0e23 -: |publisher=Nurse.nu.ac.th |date= |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Pharmaceutical Sciences<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pha.nu.ac.th/ |title=&#124; Pharmaceutical Sciences &#124; |publisher=Pha.nu.ac.th |date= |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Public Health<ref>[http://www.helth.nu.ac.th/] {{dead link|date=February 2015}}</ref>\n* The Social Sciences Cluster\n**  Faculty of Education<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edu.nu.ac.th/ |title=\u0e04\u0e13\u0e30\u0e28\u0e36\u0e01\u0e29\u0e32\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e15\u0e23\u0e4c |publisher=Edu.nu.ac.th |date= |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Humanities<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.human.nu.ac.th/ |title=\u0155\u00b8\u201e\u0155\u00b8\u201c\u0155\u00b8\u00b0\u0155\u00b8\u0104\u0155\u00b8\u2122\u0155\u00b8\u00b8\u0155\u00b8\u0160\u0155\u00b8\u02d8\u0155\u00b8\u00a8\u0155\u00b8\u02db\u0155\u00b8\u015e\u0155\u00b8\u2022\u0155\u00b8\u0141\u0155\u0161\u0152 \u0155\u00b8\u0104\u0155\u00b8\u0164\u0155\u00b8\u02db\u0155\u00b8\u00a7\u0155\u00b8\u00b4\u0155\u00b8\u2014\u0155\u00b8\u02d8\u0155\u00b8\u02db\u0155\u00b8\u013d\u0155\u00b8\u0105\u0155\u00b8\u02d8\u0155\u00b8\u2122\u0155\u0161\u20ac\u0155\u00b8\u0141\u0155\u00b8\u00a8\u0155\u00b8\u00a7\u0155\u00b8\u0141 :: Faculty of Humanities Naresuan University |publisher=Human.nu.ac.th |date=2014-12-22 |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Law<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.nu.ac.th/ |title=F a c u l t y of L a w : \u0e04\u0e13\u0e30\u0e19\u0e34\u0e15\u0e34\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e15\u0e23\u0e4c \u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32\u0e25\u0e31\u0e22\u0e19\u0e40\u0e23\u0e28\u0e27\u0e23 |publisher=Law.nu.ac.th |date= |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Business Economics and Communications<ref>[http://www.mis.nu.ac.th/]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060614004229/http://www.mis.nu.ac.th/ |date=June 14, 2006 }}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Social Sciences<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.social.nu.ac.th/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031225202224/http://www.social.nu.ac.th/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 December 2003 |title=Faculty of Social Sciences |publisher=Social.nu.ac.th |accessdate=23 February 2015 }}</ref>\n* The Science & Technology Cluster\n**  Faculty of Agriculture, Natural Resources & Environment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agi.nu.ac.th/ |title=Faculty of Agriculture, Natural Resources and Environment |publisher=Agi.nu.ac.th |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Architecture<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arch.nu.ac.th/ |title=\u00a4\u0142\u0110\u0118\u015b\u0147\u0165\u0143\u013e\u00c2\u0104\u0102\u0102\u00c1\u010c\u0147\u0118\u013e\u0102\u011b |publisher=Arch.nu.ac.th |date= |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Engineering<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eng.nu.ac.th/ |title=Faculty of Engineering |publisher=Eng.nu.ac.th |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Science<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sci.nu.ac.th/ |title=Faculty of Science |publisher=Sci.nu.ac.th |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n[[Image:NU Library.JPG|300px|thumb|right| New central library]]\n\nOther [[school]]s, [[college]]s and [[institute]]s organized by Naresuan University:\n*  School of Renewable Energy Technology (SERT)<ref>{{cite 