:Phitsanulok]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Phitsanulok Province]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1990]]\n[[Category:1990 establishments in Thailand]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates}}\n{{about|a university in Thailand|other uses|Naresuan (disambiguation)}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Naresuan University\n| native_name = \u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32\u0e25\u0e31\u0e22\u0e19\u0e40\u0e23\u0e28\u0e27\u0e23\n| image = [[Image:Naresuanlogo.jpg|150 px| Naresuan University emblem]]\n| established = {{start date|1990|7|29}}\n| type = [[Public university|Public]]\n| president = Prof. Dr. Kanchana Ngourungsi\n| undergrad = 25,721\n| postgrad = 5,020\n| city = [[Mueang Phitsanulok District]]\n| country = [[Thailand]]\n| coor = {{coord|16|44|43|N|100|11|28|E|region:TH-56_type:edu_source:dewiki|display=inline,title}}\n| colours = Grey and orange\n| website = http://old.nu.ac.th/en/; http://www.nu.ac.th/\n| affiliations = [[Association of Southeast Asian Institutions of Higher Learning|ASAIHL]]\n}}\n\n'''Naresuan University''' (NU) ({{lang-th|\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32\u0e25\u0e31\u0e22\u0e19\u0e40\u0e23\u0e28\u0e27\u0e23}}, {{IPA-th|m\u0101.h\u01ce\u02d0.w\u00edt.t\u02b0\u0101.j\u0101\u02d0.l\u0101j n\u0101.r\u0113\u02d0.s\u01d4a\u032fn|pron}}) is a government university in [[Phitsanulok Province]], northern [[Thailand]]. It was established as a separate university on 29 July 1990, the 400th anniversary of the start of the reign of Phitsanulok-born King [[Naresuan]] the Great. A courtyard with a statue of King Naresuan is on the campus grounds and students regularly pay their respects before it. The university has about 20,000 full-time students.\n\n==History==\nOn 18 January 1964, the Ministry of Education resolved to create branches of the Bangkok's College of Education in each region of the country. On 25 January 1967, the Phitsanulok campus was established as the fourth branch of the College of Education and was meant to serve mainly the northern provinces.\n\nIn 1974 the College of Education was upgraded to university status and was named [[Srinakharinwirot University]]. Originally, only the third and fourth years of university study were offered at Phitsanulok, and students were admitted by competitive examination after completing the curriculum at one of the nation's associate degree level teacher training colleges. In 1976, the first and second years were added. Other majors besides education were gradually included, and in 1990 the Phitsanulok campus became independent of Srinakarinwirot University. It was designated \"Naresuan University\" during the celebrations of the 400th anniversary of King Naresuan the Great's ascension to the throne.\n\n[[Image:KingNU.jpg|200px|thumb|right| King Naresuan the Great statue, Naresuan University]]\n\nNaresuan University has a second campus in [[Phayao]], which opened in 1999 and was upgraded to university level and named \"[[University of Phayao]]\" in 2010. It also offers extension courses across the country at nine education centers, including [[Bangkok]].\n\n==Ranking==\nIn September 2006, Naresuan University was ranked as \"Very Good\" in a study conducted on Thai universities by the Commission on Higher Education and 5th in the uniRank 2017 Thai University Ranking.\n\n==Faculties==\nThe university has 16 [[Faculty (division)|faculties]], organized into three clusters:<ref>{{cite web |title=Faculties/Colleges/Schools |url=http://old.nu.ac.th/en/b1_faculties_colleges_schools.php |website=Naresuan University |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n* The Health Sciences Cluster\n**  Faculty of Allied Health Sciences<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ahs.nu.ac.th/ |title=Allied Health Servies |publisher=Ahs.nu.ac.th |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Dentistry<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dent.nu.ac.th/ |title=Faculty of Dentistry |publisher=Dent.nu.ac.th |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref> \n**  Faculty of Medical Science<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.medsci.nu.ac.th/ |title=Faculty of Medical Science |publisher=Medsci.nu.ac.th |date= |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n**  [[Faculty of Medicine Naresuan University|Faculty of Medicine]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.med.nu.ac.th |title=:: Faculty of Medicine :: Nareasuan University :: |publisher=Med.nu.ac.th |date=2014-08-31 |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n*** [[Naresuan University Hospital]]<ref>[http://www.nuh.nu.ac.th]   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060708114010/http://www.nuh.nu.ac.th/ |date=July 8, 2006 }}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Nursing<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nurse.nu.ac.th/ |title=:- \u0e04\u0e13\u0e30\u0e1e\u0e22\u0e32\u0e1a\u0e32\u0e25\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e15\u0e23\u0e4c \u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32\u0e25\u0e31\u0e22\u0e19\u0e40\u0e23\u0e28\u0e27\u0e23 -: |publisher=Nurse.nu.ac.th |date= |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Pharmaceutical Sciences<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pha.nu.ac.th/ |title=&#124; Pharmaceutical Sciences &#124; |publisher=Pha.nu.ac.th |date= |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Public Health<ref>[http://www.helth.nu.ac.th/] {{dead link|date=February 2015}}</ref>\n* The Social Sciences Cluster\n**  Faculty of Education<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edu.nu.ac.th/ |title=\u0e04\u0e13\u0e30\u0e28\u0e36\u0e01\u0e29\u0e32\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e15\u0e23\u0e4c |publisher=Edu.nu.ac.th |date= |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Humanities<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.human.nu.ac.th/ |title=\u0155\u00b8\u201e\u0155\u00b8\u201c\u0155\u00b8\u00b0\u0155\u00b8\u0104\u0155\u00b8\u2122\u0155\u00b8\u00b8\u0155\u00b8\u0160\u0155\u00b8\u02d8\u0155\u00b8\u00a8\u0155\u00b8\u02db\u0155\u00b8\u015e\u0155\u00b8\u2022\u0155\u00b8\u0141\u0155\u0161\u0152 \u0155\u00b8\u0104\u0155\u00b8\u0164\u0155\u00b8\u02db\u0155\u00b8\u00a7\u0155\u00b8\u00b4\u0155\u00b8\u2014\u0155\u00b8\u02d8\u0155\u00b8\u02db\u0155\u00b8\u013d\u0155\u00b8\u0105\u0155\u00b8\u02d8\u0155\u00b8\u2122\u0155\u0161\u20ac\u0155\u00b8\u0141\u0155\u00b8\u00a8\u0155\u00b8\u00a7\u0155\u00b8\u0141 :: Faculty of Humanities Naresuan University |publisher=Human.nu.ac.th |date=2014-12-22 |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Law<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.nu.ac.th/ |title=F a c u l t y of L a w : \u0e04\u0e13\u0e30\u0e19\u0e34\u0e15\u0e34\u0e28\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e15\u0e23\u0e4c \u0e21\u0e2b\u0e32\u0e27\u0e34\u0e17\u0e22\u0e32\u0e25\u0e31\u0e22\u0e19\u0e40\u0e23\u0e28\u0e27\u0e23 |publisher=Law.nu.ac.th |date= |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Business Economics and Communications<ref>[http://www.mis.nu.ac.th/]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060614004229/http://www.mis.nu.ac.th/ |date=June 14, 2006 }}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Social Sciences<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.social.nu.ac.th/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20031225202224/http://www.social.nu.ac.th/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 December 2003 |title=Faculty of Social Sciences |publisher=Social.nu.ac.th |accessdate=23 February 2015 }}</ref>\n* The Science & Technology Cluster\n**  Faculty of Agriculture, Natural Resources & Environment<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agi.nu.ac.th/ |title=Faculty of Agriculture, Natural Resources and Environment |publisher=Agi.nu.ac.th |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Architecture<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arch.nu.ac.th/ |title=\u00a4\u0142\u0110\u0118\u015b\u0147\u0165\u0143\u013e\u00c2\u0104\u0102\u0102\u00c1\u010c\u0147\u0118\u013e\u0102\u011b |publisher=Arch.nu.ac.th |date= |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Engineering<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eng.nu.ac.th/ |title=Faculty of Engineering |publisher=Eng.nu.ac.th |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n**  Faculty of Science<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sci.nu.ac.th/ |title=Faculty of Science |publisher=Sci.nu.ac.th |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n[[Image:NU Library.JPG|300px|thumb|right| New central library]]\n\nOther [[school]]s, [[college]]s and [[institute]]s organized by Naresuan University:\n*  School of Renewable Energy Technology (SERT)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sert.nu.ac.th/ |title=School Of Renewable Energy Technology |publisher=Sert.nu.ac.th |date= |accessdate=2015-02-23}}</ref>\n*  Naresuan University International College (NUIC)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nuic.nu.ac.th/ |title=NUIC |publisher=Nuic.nu.ac.th |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n*  Graduate School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.grad.nu.ac.th/ |title=The Graduate School |publisher=Grad.nu.ac.th |accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n*  Naresuan Institute for Community Empowerment (NICE)<ref>[http://www.nu.ac.th/nice/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120204194610/http://www.nu.ac.th/nice/ |date=February 4, 2012 }}</ref>\n*  Institute of Research and Development Administration (IRDA)<ref>[http://www.research.nu.ac.th/home/index.php/ ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070223172844/http://www.research.nu.ac.th/home/index.php/ |date=February 23, 2007 }}</ref>\n* Center of ASEAN Community Studies (CACS) <ref>https://cacs.nu.ac.th/</ref>\n[[Image:QSbuilding.JPG|300px|thumb|right| Queen Sirikit lecture hall and theater]]\n\n==Naresuan University Art and Culture Gallery==\nThe Naresuan University Art and Culture Gallery holds over 100 artistic works by culturally significant Thai artists.\n\n==Partner Institution==\n===Malaysia===\n*[[Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman]]<ref name=\"UTARUniversityPartners\">{{cite web|url=http://www2.utar.edu.my/dcinternet/index.jsp?fcatid=7819|title=University Partners - Division of Community and International Networking|publisher=Universiti Tunku Abdul Rahman(UTAR)|accessdate=25 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Philippines===\n* San Sebastian College - Recoletos\n\n==See also==\n* [[Naresuan University Hospital]]\n* [[Education in Thailand]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Naresuan University}}\n* [http://www.nu.ac.th/en/ Naresuan University website]\n\n{{Universities in Thailand}}\n\n[[Category:Universities in Thailand]]\n[[Category:Phitsanulok]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Phitsanulok Province]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1990]]\n[[Category:1990 establishments in Thailand]]\n", "name_user": "Seligne", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFaculties", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naresuan_University"}
{"title_page": "Anorak (slang)", "text_new": "{{short description|British slang term referring to a person who has a very strong interest, perhaps obsessive, in niche subjects}}\n{{Wiktionary|anorak}}\n\"'''Anorak'''\" {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u00e6|n|\u0259r|\u00e6|k}} is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[slang]] which refers to a person who has a very strong interest, perhaps obsessive, in niche subjects. This interest may be unacknowledged or not understood by the general public. The term is sometimes used synonymously with \"[[geek]]\" or \"[[nerd]]\", the Spanish term \"friki\", or the Japanese term \"[[otaku]]\", albeit referring to different niches.\n\n==Etymology==\nIn 1984 the ''[[The Observer|Observer]]'' newspaper used the term as a [[metonym]] for the prototype group interested in detailed trivia, the [[trainspotter]]s,<ref name=Games2007>{{Citation\n | last = Games\n | first = Alex\n | year = 2007\n | title = Balderdash & piffle : one sandwich short of a dog's dinner\n | isbn = 978-1-84607-235-2\n | publisher = BBC\n | location = London\n | url-access = registration\n | url = https://archive.org/details/balderdashpiffle0000game\n }}</ref><ref>[http://oxforddictionaries.com/definition/anorak?view=uk Oxford Dictionaries: anorak, definition 2] Retrieved 2011-06-05</ref> as members of this group often wore unfashionable but warm [[parka]]s called \"anoraks\" when standing for hours on station platforms or along railway tracks, noting down details of passing trains.\n\nThe first use of the phrase to describe an obsessive fan has also been credited to the radio presenter [[Andy Archer (radio presenter)|Andy Archer]], who used the term in the early 1970s for fans of [[Pirate radio in the United Kingdom|offshore radio]], who would charter boats to come out to sea to visit the radio ships.<ref>{{cite book|title=Pop Went the Pirates II|first=Keith|last=Skues|authorlink=Keith Skues|publisher=Lambs' Meadow Publications|place=[[Horning]]|isbn=978-0-907398-05-9|year=2009|page=37}}</ref>\n     \nIn 1983, the first edition of the ''Anoraks UK Weekly Report'' was published, featuring news of pirate radio broadcasts.<ref>{{cite web |title=The weekly reports |date=1983 |work=Anoraks UK - Index |url=http://www.dxarchive.com/press_anoraks_uk_index.html#1983 |via=DX Archive |accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Examples of use==\n* [[Roy Cropper]], a character from the popular British soap opera ''[[Coronation Street]]'', is a stereotypical portrayal of an \"anorak\".\n* In 1992, [[BBC Television|BBC TV]] broadcast the [[Dr Who]] documentary ''Resistance Is Useless'', in which British actor [[Steve Steen]] provided the voice of a faceless anorak-clad narrator known as ''The Anorak''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Resistance Is Useless|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0328791/ |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Former British [[Prime Minister]] [[John Major]], derided by many for perceived dullness, was described by [[Anthony Seldon]] as an \"obsessive political anorak\".<ref>Seldon, Anthony. ''John Major: A Political Life.'' London: Weidenfeld & Nicolson, 1998.</ref>\n* [[Indie pop]] band [[Another Sunny Day]] released a single called \"Anorak City\" in 1988 on [[Sarah Records]]. The \"anoraks\" described in the lyrics are independent pop fans.\n* [[Progressive rock]] band [[Marillion]] titled their twelfth studio album ''[[Anoraknophobia]]'', released in 2001, referring to the long running in-joke that Marillion fans are sometimes called freaks or anoraks.  The album cover, tour edition releases, and related press materials feature cartoon graphics of a boy wearing a rain parka in different colors, and holding a wire coat hanger by its hook.<ref>{{cite web |author=Marillion |title=Anoraknophobia |work=Racket Records |date=1 May 2001 |url=http://www.marillion.com/music/albums/anorak.htm |accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>  Inside the liner notes for the deluxe edition of the album, there is a photograph of each of the band members posed in a similar manner, and standing near a telephone box.\n* In the 2011 [[Ernest Cline]] novel ''[[Ready Player One]]'', \"Anorak\" is the name of James Halliday's [[Avatar (computing)|avatar]].<ref>Cline, Ernest (2011). ''Ready Player One''. Random House. p. 54. {{ISBN|978-0307887443}}</ref>\n* The 2006 BBC TV detective drama series ''[[Mayo (TV series)|Mayo]]'' featured a crime scene expert nicknamed Anorak.\n* ''[[Anorak of Fire]]'' is a 1998 TV movie about a teenaged trainspotter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0203306/ |title=Anorak of Fire (1998) |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |publisher=Internet Movie Database |accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>[[File:Raucoules-Brossettes festival vapeur mai 2011.jpg|thumb|French steam anoraks in jackets]]\n* [[Terry Pratchett]] mentions them frequently in his [[Discworld]] novel \"[[Raising Steam]]\", in the classic sense, as the preferred garb for trainspotting railway enthusiasts.\n\n== Background  ==\n\nMichaela Simon{{who|date=December 2019}} saw a close connection between geeks (\"anoraks\") and [[high-functioning autism]]. Simon's article exhibits one of the rare uses of \"anorak\" as a synonym of nerd or spotter in the German language.<ref>[https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Die-Geek-Autismus-Connection-3519189.html Die Geek-Autismus-Connection, Michaela Simon 25.03.2002 Telepolis], given synonyms in the german text comprise \"Nerd, anorak, train-spotter, space-cadet, card-board, cut-out, geek, oddball, weirdo, bufty\"</ref> [[Tony Attwood]] went as far as to write a book called ''Confessions of an Autism Anorak'', stating his own obsession with the topic. He explains further connections between autism as such and the anorak status in general,<ref>Autism, Access and Inclusion on the Front Line: Confessions of an Autism Anorak Anthony Attwood, Jessica Kingsley Publishers, 24.03.2006</ref> based on the ''extreme male brain'' theory of [[Simon Baron-Cohen]].<ref>Trends Cogn Sci. 2002 Jun 1;6(6):248-254., The extreme male brain theory of autism. Baron-Cohen</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anorak (Slang)}}\n[[Category:English-language slang]]\n[[Category:Pejorative terms for people]]\n[[Category:Transport culture]]\n[[Category:Fandom]]\n[[Category:History of subcultures]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1980s]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British slang term referring to a person who has a very strong interest, perhaps obsessive, in niche subjects}}\n{{Wiktionary|anorak}}\n\"'''Anorak'''\" {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u00e6|n|\u0259r|\u00e6|k}} is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[slang]] which refers to a person who has a very strong interest, perhaps obsessive, in niche subjects. This interest may be unacknowledged or not understood by the general public. The term is sometimes used synonymously with \"[[geek]]\" or \"[[nerd]]\", the Spanish term \"friki\", or the Japanese term \"[[otaku]]\", albeit referring to different niches.\n\n==Etymology==\nIn 1984 the ''[[The Observer|Observer]]'' newspaper used the term as a [[metonym]] for the prototype group interested in detailed trivia, the [[trainspotter]]s,<ref name=Games2007>{{Citation\n | last = Games\n | first = Alex\n | year = 2007\n | title = Balderdash & piffle : one sandwich short of a dog's dinner\n | isbn = 978-1-84607-235-2\n | publisher = BBC\n | location = London\n | url-access = registration\n | url = https://archive.org/details/balderdashpiffle0000game\n }}</ref><ref>[http://oxforddictionaries.com/definition/anorak?view=uk Oxford Dictionaries: anorak, definition 2] Retrieved 2011-06-05</ref> as members of this group often wore unfashionable but warm [[parka]]s called \"anoraks\" when standing for hours on station platforms or along railway tracks, noting down details of passing trains.\n\nThe first use of the phrase to describe an obsessive fan has also been credited to the radio presenter [[Andy Archer (radio presenter)|Andy Archer]], who used the term in the early 1970s for fans of [[Pirate radio in the United Kingdom|offshore radio]], who would charter boats to come out to sea to visit the radio ships.<ref>{{cite book|title=Pop Went the Pirates II|first=Keith|last=Skues|authorlink=Keith Skues|publisher=Lambs' Meadow Publications|place=[[Horning]]|isbn=978-0-907398-05-9|year=2009|page=37}}</ref>\n     \nIn 1983, the first edition of the ''Anoraks UK Weekly Report'' was published, featuring news of pirate radio broadcasts.<ref>{{cite web |title=The weekly reports |date=1983 |work=Anoraks UK - Index |url=http://www.dxarchive.com/press_anoraks_uk_index.html#1983 |via=DX Archive |accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Examples of use==\n* [[Roy Cropper]], a character from the popular British soap opera ''[[Coronation Street]]'', is a stereotypical portrayal of an \"anorak\".\n* In 1992, [[BBC Television|BBC TV]] broadcast the [[Dr Who]] documentary ''Resistance Is Useless'', in which British actor [[Steve Steen]] provided the voice of an faceless anorak-clad narrator known as ''The Anorak''.<ref>{{cite web |title=Resistance Is Useless| |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0328791/ |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n* Former British [[Prime Minister]] [[John Major]], derided by many for perceived dullness, was described by [[Anthony Seldon]] as an \"obsessive political anorak\".<ref>Seldon, Anthony. ''John Major: A Political Life.'' London: Weidenfeld & Nicolson, 1998.</ref>\n* [[Indie pop]] band [[Another Sunny Day]] released a single called \"Anorak City\" in 1988 on [[Sarah Records]]. The \"anoraks\" described in the lyrics are independent pop fans.\n* [[Progressive rock]] band [[Marillion]] titled their twelfth studio album ''[[Anoraknophobia]]'', released in 2001, referring to the long running in-joke that Marillion fans are sometimes called freaks or anoraks.  The album cover, tour edition releases, and related press materials feature cartoon graphics of a boy wearing a rain parka in different colors, and holding a wire coat hanger by its hook.<ref>{{cite web |author=Marillion |title=Anoraknophobia |work=Racket Records |date=1 May 2001 |url=http://www.marillion.com/music/albums/anorak.htm |accessdate=15 March 2018}}</ref>  Inside the liner notes for the deluxe edition of the album, there is a photograph of each of the band members posed in a similar manner, and standing near a telephone box.\n* In the 2011 [[Ernest Cline]] novel ''[[Ready Player One]]'', \"Anorak\" is the name of James Halliday's [[Avatar (computing)|avatar]].<ref>Cline, Ernest (2011). ''Ready Player One''. Random House. p. 54. {{ISBN|978-0307887443}}</ref>\n* The 2006 BBC TV detective drama series ''[[Mayo (TV series)|Mayo]]'' featured a crime scene expert nicknamed Anorak.\n* ''[[Anorak of Fire]]'' is a 1998 TV movie about a teenaged trainspotter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0203306/ |title=Anorak of Fire (1998) |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |publisher=Internet Movie Database |accessdate=14 January 2014}}</ref>[[File:Raucoules-Brossettes festival vapeur mai 2011.jpg|thumb|French steam anoraks in jackets]]\n* [[Terry Pratchett]] mentions them frequently in his [[Discworld]] novel \"[[Raising Steam]]\", in the classic sense, as the preferred garb for trainspotting railway enthusiasts.\n\n== Background  ==\n\nMichaela Simon{{who|date=December 2019}} saw a close connection between geeks (\"anoraks\") and [[high-functioning autism]]. Simon's article exhibits one of the rare uses of \"anorak\" as a synonym of nerd or spotter in the German language.<ref>[https://www.heise.de/tp/features/Die-Geek-Autismus-Connection-3519189.html Die Geek-Autismus-Connection, Michaela Simon 25.03.2002 Telepolis], given synomyms in the german text comprise \"Nerd, anorak, train-spotter, space-cadet, card-board, cut-out, geek, oddball, weirdo, bufty\"</ref> [[Tony Attwood]] went as far as to write a book called ''Confessions of an Autism Anorak'', stating his own obsession with the topic. He explains further connections between autism as such and the anorak status in general,<ref>Autism, Access and Inclusion on the Front Line: Confessions of an Autism Anorak Anthony Attwood, Jessica Kingsley Publishers, 24.03.2006</ref> based on the ''extreme male brain'' theory of [[Simon Baron-Cohen]].<ref>Trends Cogn Sci. 2002 Jun 1;6(6):248-254., The extreme male brain theory of autism. Baron-Cohen</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anorak (Slang)}}\n[[Category:English-language slang]]\n[[Category:Pejorative terms for people]]\n[[Category:Transport culture]]\n[[Category:Fandom]]\n[[Category:History of subcultures]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 1980s]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: an faceless \u2192 a faceless, synomyms \u2192 synonyms", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anorak_(slang)"}
{"title_page": "Ben Platt", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Ben Platt\n| image              = Ben-Platt at 2020 Grammys.jpg\n| caption            = Platt in 2020\n| birth_name         = Benjamin Schiff Platt\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1993|09|24}}\n| birth_place        = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n*Actor\n*singer\n}}\n| father             = [[Marc Platt (producer)|Marc Platt]]\n| years_active       = 2002\u2013present\n| website            = {{URL|benplattmusic.com}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist | embed = yes\n| background    = solo_singer\n| genre         = {{flatlist|\n* [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]\n* [[pop music|pop]]\n}}\n| instrument    = \n| label         = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Benjamin Schiff Platt''' (born September 24, 1993)<ref name=\"ap birthday\">{{cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/pmn/entertainment-pmn/celeb-birthdays-for-the-week-of-sept-24-30|title=Celeb birthdays for the week of Sept. 24\u201330|date=September 19, 2017|agency=[[Associated Press]]|via=[[National Post]]|accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref> is an American actor, singer, and songwriter. He began his career in theater as a child and has appeared in [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] productions of ''[[The Music Man]]'' (2002), ''[[The Book of Mormon (musical)|The Book of Mormon]]'' (2012\u20132013), and ''[[Dear Evan Hansen]]'' (2015\u20132017), receiving multiple accolades for his performance as the title character in the latter, including the 2017 [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tony Awards 2017: Complete Winners List|url=https://variety.com/2017/legit/awards/tony-awards-2017-winners-list-1202461975/|accessdate=July 8, 2017|work=Variety|date=June 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Chow|first=Andrew R.|title=2017 Tony Awards Winners|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/11/theater/tony-winners-list.html|accessdate=July 8, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=June 11, 2017}}</ref> Platt's film credits include roles in ''[[Pitch Perfect]]'' (2012), ''[[Pitch Perfect 2]]'' (2015), and ''[[Ricki and the Flash]]'' (2015). He currently stars in the [[Netflix]] TV show [[The Politician (TV series)|''The Politician'']], for which he was nominated for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]] in 2019.\n\nPlatt signed with [[Atlantic Records]] in 2017 and released his debut studio album, ''[[Sing to Me Instead]]'', in March 2019.\n\n==Early life and education==\nPlatt was born in [[Los Angeles]], the fourth of five children of Julie (n\u00e9e Beren) and [[Marc Platt (producer)|Marc Platt]]. His father is a film, television, and theater producer whose credits include ''[[Legally Blonde]]'', [[Into the Woods (film)|''Into The Woods'']], [[La La Land (film)|''La La Land'']], ''[[Mary Poppins Returns]]'', and the musical ''[[Wicked (musical)|Wicked]]''.<ref name=depaulia>{{cite web|url=http://www.depauliaonline.com/focus/digging-into-the-book-of-mormon-an-interview-with-ben-platt-and-nic-rouleau-1.3007685|title=Digging into \"The Book of Mormon\": an interview with Ben Platt and Nic Rouleau|website=Depaulia Online|access-date=October 22, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131023061306/http://www.depauliaonline.com/focus/digging-into-the-book-of-mormon-an-interview-with-ben-platt-and-nic-rouleau-1.3007685#.UmYePHDrzQc|archive-date=October 23, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He and his family are [[Jewish]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upenn.edu/gazette/0506/feature1_2.html|title=Ben Platt Profile|work=University of Pennsylvania|accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timesofisrael.com/tony-award-winner-ben-platts-journey-from-camp-ramah-to-broadway/|title=Tony Award-winner Ben Platt's journey from Camp Ramah to Broadway|work=The Times of Israel|date=June 14, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tabletmag.com/scroll/242062/jewcy-ramah-broadway-ben-platt-caissie-levy-ethan-slater|title=Three Camp Ramah Alums Now Have Leading Roles on Broadway. What's in the Bug Juice|work=Tablet Magazine|date=July 31, 2017|accessdate=April 18, 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe attended the Adderley School for Performing Arts in [[Pacific Palisades, Los Angeles|Pacific Palisades]], performing in productions like ''[[Bye Bye Birdie]]'' and ''[[Into the Woods]]''. Platt attended [[Harvard-Westlake School]] in Los Angeles, graduating in 2011. He then enrolled at [[Columbia University]] in New York but dropped out after six weeks to fulfill his contract with ''[[The Book of Mormon (musical)|The Book of Mormon]]''. During his time at Columbia, he was a member of the campus [[a cappella]] musical group ''Nonsequitur''.<ref name=depaulia/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.columbianonseq.com/alumni-members.html|title=Columbia Nonsequitur Alumni Members|work=Columbia Nonsequitur|accessdate=May 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===2002\u20132014: Early stage work and ''The Book of Mormon''===\nAt 9 years old, Platt played Winthrop Paroo in ''[[The Music Man]]'' at the [[Hollywood Bowl]] alongside [[Kristin Chenoweth]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bnvPQwOsZ68|title=Show People with Paul Wontorek Interview: Ben Platt of \"The Book of Mormon\" and \"Pitch Perfect\"|date=September 9, 2014|website=Broadway.com|accessdate=August 7, 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> At 11, he appeared in a brief national tour of ''[[Caroline, or Change]]'', by [[Jeanine Tesori]] and [[Tony Kushner]]. At 17, he played Jean Valjean in Kidz Theater's production of ''[[Les Mis\u00e9rables (musical)|Les Mis\u00e9rables]].'' His other early roles include the role of Claude Bukowski in Columbia University's production of ''[[Hair (musical)|Hair: The American Tribal Love-Rock Musical]]''.<ref name=\"cs\">{{cite web|url=http://www.columbiaspectator.com/2012/11/13/ben-platt-joins-book-mormon-road|first=Zoe|last=Miller|title=Ben Platt joins ''The Book of Mormon'' on the road|work=Columbia Spectator Daily|date=November 13, 2012|accessdate=October 20, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130729024722/http://www.columbiaspectator.com/2012/11/13/ben-platt-joins-book-mormon-road|archive-date=July 29, 2013|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> He has also collaborated on a workshop of ''[[Alice by Heart]]'', by [[Duncan Sheik]] and [[Steven Sater]], a new take on ''[[Alice in Wonderland (musical)|Alice in Wonderland]]''.\n\nIn 2012, Platt was cast as Elder Arnold Cunningham in the Chicago production of ''[[The Book of Mormon (musical)|The Book of Mormon]]''. The show premiered at the [[Bank of America Theatre]] on December 19, 2012, after a week of previews.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hetrick|first=Adam|title=Review: The Book of Mormon, With Nic Rouleau, Ben Platt and Syesha Mercado, Opens in Chicago Dec. 19|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/the-book-of-mormon-with-nic-rouleau-ben-platt-and-syesha-mercado-opens-in-chicago-dec-19-com-200817|work=Playbill|date=December 19, 2012}}</ref> The production was well received and closed on October 6, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hetrick|first=Adam|title=Review: Chicago Engagement of&nbsp;The Book of Mormon&nbsp;Ends Oct. 6|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/chicago-engagement-of-the-book-of-mormon-ends-oct-6-com-205537|accessdate=November 28, 2017|work=Playbill|date=October 6, 2013}}</ref> Critics lauded Platt's performance, calling him a \"true revelation in this brand new Chicago production...He really leans into this part, throwing himself out there with the abandonment of youth\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Reid|first=Kelly|title=Review: Ben Platt steals the show as Elder Cunningham in 'Book of Mormon'|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/theater/chi-ben-platt-book-of-mormon-2012-story,amp.html#ampshare=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/theater/chi-ben-platt-book-of-mormon-2012-story.html|accessdate=November 28, 2017|work=The Chicago Tribune|date=December 2, 2012}}</ref> Platt later reprised his role as Elder Cunningham on [[Broadway Theatre (53rd Street)|Broadway]] at the [[Eugene O'Neill Theatre]] from January 7, 2014 to January 6, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hetrick|first=Adam|title=Review: Ben Platt, Nic Rouleau and Syesha Mercado Are New Stars of ''The Book of Mormon'' on Broadway|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/ben-platt-nic-rouleau-and-syesha-mercado-are-new-stars-of-the-book-of-mormon-on-broadway-com-213523|accessdate=November 28, 2017|work=Playbill|date=January 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2015\u20132017: Film career and ''Dear Evan Hansen''===\nIn 2012, Platt had a supporting role in the musical comedy ''[[Pitch Perfect]]'', loosely based on the non-fiction book ''Pitch Perfect: The Quest for Collegiate A Cappella Glory''. Platt played the magic-loving Benji Applebaum, alongside an ensemble cast comprising [[Anna Kendrick]], [[Skylar Astin]], [[Rebel Wilson]], [[Adam DeVine]], [[Anna Camp]], and [[Brittany Snow]]. The film emerged as a major commercial success and received mostly positive reviews from critics. He was subsequently nominated at a [[Teen Choice Awards]] in the category Choice Movie: Male Scene Stealer for his work.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000644/2013|title=Teen Choice Awards (2013)|accessdate=May 20, 2017}}</ref> In 2015, Platt reprised his role as Benji Applebaum in the sequel, ''[[Pitch Perfect 2]]''. He has since made film appearances in ''[[Ricki and the Flash]]'' and ''[[Billy Lynn's Long Halftime Walk (film)|Billy Lynn's Long Halftime Walk]]''.\n\nPlatt became attached to [[Pasek and Paul]]'s then ''Untitled P&P Project'' in 2014, participating in early read-throughs and workshops.<ref>{{cite web|last=Marks|first=Peter|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/amphtml/entertainment/theater_dance/dear-evan-hansen-the-trail-of-a-musical-comet/2017/06/06/bff6d580-4579-11e7-98cd-af64b4fe2dfc_story.html#ampshare=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/theater_dance/dear-evan-hansen-the-trail-of-a-musical-comet/2017/06/06/bff6d580-4579-11e7-98cd-af64b4fe2dfc_story.html|title=How 'Dear Evan Hansen' became one of the most remarkable shows in musical-theater history|work=The Washington Post|date=June 7, 2017}}</ref> By 2015, the musical, titled ''[[Dear Evan Hansen]]'', had begun production in [[Washington, D.C.]] at the [[Arena Stage]] with Platt originating the titular role. The show premiered on July 9, 2015 and closed August 23, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gioia|first=Michael|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/pasek-and-pauls-dear-evan-hansen-about-the-high-school-struggle-to-fit-in-premieres-in-d.c-355138#|title=Pasek and Paul's Dear Evan Hansen, About the High School Struggle to Fit In, Premieres in D.C.|work=[[Playbill]]|date=July 30, 2015}}</ref> The overwhelming positive reception toward the production and Platt's performance resulted in the show being transferred to [[Off-Broadway]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Cox|first=Gordon|url=https://variety.com/2015/legit/news/dear-evan-hansen-musical-off-broadway-second-stage-theater-1201569707/|title=Buzzy Musical 'Dear Evan Hansen' Sets New York Run|work=Variety|date=August 13, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Platt once again originated the role of Evan Hansen at [[Second Stage Theatre]]. Platt and the cast played a month of previews, beginning on March 26, 2016, before premiering on May 1, 2016. The limited engagement sold out its entire run with Platt playing his last performance on May 26, 2016.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|last=Clement|first=Olivia|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/ben-platt-to-star-in-ny-premiere-of-new-musical-dear-evan-hansen-383684#|title=Ben Platt to Star in NY Premiere of New Musical 'Dear Evan Hansen'|work=[[Playbill]]|date=February 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Gioia|first=Michael|url=http://www.playbill.com/news/article/following-its-d.c.-run-pasek-and-pauls-dear-evan-hansen-will-transfer-to-new-york-357645#|title=Following Its D.C. Run, Pasek and Paul's ''Dear Evan Hansen'' Will Transfer to New York|work=[[Playbill]]|date=August 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Clement|first=Olivia|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/dear-evan-hansen-begins-tonight-com-383684#|title=Pasek and Paul's 'Dear Evan Hansen' Bows in New York|work=[[Playbill]]|date=March 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:BenPlattInAnElevator.jpg|thumb|Ben Platt in 2017]]\nIn December 2016, Platt originated the title role in ''Dear Evan Hansen'' on [[Broadway Theatre (53rd Street)|Broadway]] at the [[Music Box Theatre]]. Critics hailed his work, calling it \"historic\" and \"one of the greatest leading male performances ever seen in a musical\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Isherwood|first=Charles|title=Review: In 'Dear Evan Hansen,' a Lonely Teenager, a Viral Lie and a Breakout Star|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/12/04/theater/dear-evan-hansen-review.html|accessdate=July 8, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=December 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Marks|first=Peter|title=How 'Dear Evan Hansen' became one of the most remarkable shows in musical-theater history|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/theater_dance/dear-evan-hansen-the-trail-of-a-musical-comet/2017/06/06/bff6d580-4579-11e7-98cd-af64b4fe2dfc_story.html|accessdate=July 8, 2017|work=The Washington Post|date=June 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/newyork/blog/broadway-review-dear-evan-hansen-is-lit-by-a-dazzling-star-turn-120416|title=Broadway review: Dear Evan Hansen is lit by a dazzling star turn|website=TimeOut.com|accessdate=August 7, 2017}}</ref> For his performance, Platt won numerous awards including the [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical]]. Platt played his final performance on November 19, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/ben-platt-sets-departure-date-from-broadways-dear-evan-hansen|title=Ben Platt Sets Departure Date from Broadway's Dear Evan Hansen|first=Olivia|last=Clement|work=Playbill|date=August 15, 2017|accessdate=September 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn November 29, 2018, it was announced that [[Universal Pictures]] and Platt's father, [[Marc Platt (producer)|Marc Platt]], secured the film rights to the musical.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/11/dear-evan-hansen-film-tony-award-winning-musical-wonder-stephen-chbosky-marc-platt-1202222391/|title=Tony Award-Winning Musical 'Dear Evan Hansen' Will Be Universal Pictures, Marc Platt Film; 'Wonder's Stephen Chbosky May Direct|first1=Anita|last1=Busch|first2=Anita|last2=Busch|date=November 29, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/dear-evan-hansen-movie-universal-1203048797/|title=Broadway Musical 'Dear Evan Hansen' Getting Movie Treatment|first1=Justin|last1=Kroll|first2=Justin|last2=Kroll|date=November 29, 2018|publisher=|accessdate=February 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2017\u2013present: Music and ''The Politician''===\nIn 2017, Platt signed a record deal with [[Atlantic Records]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Milzoff|first1=Rebecca|title=''Dear Evan Hansen'' Tony-Winner Ben Platt Signs With Atlantic Records: Exclusive|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/7957647/ben-platt-atlantic-records-signs-dear-evan-hansen-tony-winner|accessdate=September 11, 2017|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|date=September 7, 2017|location=United States}}</ref> On January 28, 2018, he performed [[Leonard Bernstein]]'s \"[[Somewhere (song)|Somewhere]]\" live at the [[60th Annual Grammy Awards]] accompanied by [[Justin Goldner]] and Adele Stein and arranged by [[Alex Lacamoire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/videos/ben-platt-somewhere-2018-grammys-performance|title=Ben Platt \"Somewhere\": GRAMMY Performance|date=January 29, 2018|work=GRAMMY.com|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/LacketyLac/status/957770741587632128|title=Alex Lacamoire on Twitter|website=Twitter.com|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn March 19, 2018, Platt and ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]'' creator [[Lin-Manuel Miranda]] released \"Found/Tonight\", a [[mashup (music)|mashup]] of the ''Hamilton'' song \"The Story of Tonight\" and the ''Dear Evan Hansen'' song \"You Will Be Found\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ew.com/music/2018/03/19/lin-manuel-miranda-ben-platt-found-tonight/|title=Lin-Manuel Miranda, Ben Platt release 'Hamilton'/'Dear Evan Hansen' mash-up 'Found/Tonight'|work=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref> Platt donated a portion of the proceeds to support the [[March for Our Lives]] anti-gun-violence initiative, and also performed on stage with Miranda at the rally in [[Washington, D.C.]] on March 24, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kreps|first=Daniel|title=See Lin-Manuel Miranda, Ben Platt Perform at March for Our Lives Rally|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/lin-manuel-miranda-ben-platt-perform-at-march-for-our-lives-w518349|accessdate=March 28, 2018|work=Rolling Stone|date=March 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=CBS Miami|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Tivcf-zIOU|title=Lin-Manuel Miranda, Ben Platt Perform At March For Our Lives|date=March 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|work=Atlantic Records|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wzE_HCK_gVo|title=Lin-Manuel Miranda & Ben Platt \u2013 \"Found/Tonight\" March For Our Lives Performance|date=March 26, 2018}}</ref> Platt starred opposite [[Damian Lewis]], [[Nina Dobrev]], and [[Mena Massoud]] in the [[Rob Ford]] historical fiction thriller ''[[Run This Town (film)|Run This Town]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/damian-lewis-play-controversial-toronto-mayor-rob-ford-thriller-1101298|title=Damian Lewis to Play Controversial Ex-Toronto Mayor Rob Ford in Drama|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=April 11, 2018}}</ref> The casting of Platt caused minor controversy, over allegations that the filmmakers were appropriating the story of female reporter [[Robyn Doolittle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2018/04/10/robyn-doolittle-rob-ford-movie-ben-platt-damian-lewis-run-this-town_a_23408127/|title=Rob Ford Movie Decides It Doesn't Need Kickass Female Reporter Role|date=April 10, 2018|work=HuffPost|accessdate=April 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Platt announced that his debut studio album ''[[Sing to Me Instead]]'' was scheduled for release on March 29, 2019. It was made available for pre-order, along with the songs \"Bad Habit\" and \"Ease My Mind\" a few days later. Following the release of his debut album, Platt embarked on his first North American tour in May 2019.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Lenker |first1=Maureen Lee |title=Ben Platt on his debut album, Sing to Me Instead: 'I definitely wanted to make music that sounded like me' |url=https://ew.com/music/2019/02/01/ben-platt-debut-album-bad-habit-video/ |accessdate=February 1, 2019 |magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |date=February 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Moynihan |first1=Caitlyn |title=Ben Platt Sings Out in First Music Video From Debut Album Sing to Me Instead |url=https://www.broadway.com/buzz/194773/ben-platt-sings-out-in-first-music-video-from-debut-album-sing-to-me-instead/ |accessdate=February 1, 2019 |publisher=Broadway Buzz |date=February 1, 2019}}</ref> The tour ended on September 29, 2019 at [[Radio City Music Hall]] in [[New York City]], in which the concert there was taped for release on Netflix on an unconfirmed date.<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\">https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/video/ben-platt-concert-special-headed-netflix-watch-1238421</ref> Platt released a new single \"Rain\" on August 23, 2019, followed by a music video on September 10, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/pride/8529589/ben-platt-rain-video|title=Ben Platt Is Going to Dance, 'Rain' or Shine, in New Video: Watch|website=Billboard|access-date=2019-09-11}}</ref>\n\nOn August 29, 2019, it was announced that Platt would be starring in [[Richard Linklater]]'s film adaptation of [[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|''Merrily We Roll Along'']] alongside [[Beanie Feldstein]] and [[Blake Jenner]]. The project is set to be shot over the course of twenty years, with [[principal photography]] of the first sequence of the film having already been completed prior to the announcement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/richard-linklater-merrily-we-roll-along-20-year-film-production-1202707828/|title=Richard Linklater To Shoot Stephen Sondheim Musical 'Merrily We Roll Along' Over 20 Years For Blumhouse|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|last2=D'Alessandro|first2=Anthony|date=2019-08-30|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-08-30}}</ref>\n\nPlatt currently stars as Payton Hobart on the [[Netflix]] comedy-drama series [[The Politician (TV series)|''The Politician'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/politician-star-ben-platt-playing-a-high-school-student-season-2-1254336|title='The Politician' Star Ben Platt on Playing a High School Student and What's Ahead in Season 2|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=November 19, 2019|last=Bentley|first=Jean}}</ref> Platt's casting was announced in March 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/02/ryan-murphy-series-the-politician-netflix-ben-platt-cast-barbra-streisand-gwyneth-paltrow-in-talks-to-star-1202278255/|title=Netflix Nabs Ryan Murphy Series 'The Politician'; Ben Platt Set, Barbra Streisand & Gwyneth Paltrow In Talks To Star|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=February 2018}}</ref> and the series premiered on September 27, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/reviews/the-politician-netflix-review-ben-platt-ryan-murphy-1203343878/|title=TV Review: Netflix's 'The Politician' Starring Ben Platt|website=Variety|last=Framke|first=Caroline|date=September 23, 2019}}</ref> He received a [[Golden Globe Award]] nomination for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy|Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Musical or Comedy]] for his performance in the series' first season.<ref name=\"GGA\">{{cite web|url=https://people.com/tv/golden-globes-2020-nominees-react/|title=Golden Globes 2020 Nominees Taylor Swift, Jennifer Lopez, Ben Platt and More Celebrate Their Nods|website=PEOPLE|date=December 9, 2019|last=Guglielmi|first=Jodi}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPlatt is openly [[gay]]; he [[coming out|came out]] to his family when he was twelve years old, and publicly in 2019, through the music video for his song \"Ease My Mind\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://people.com/music/ben-platt-ease-my-mind-music-video-premiere/|title=Ben Platt Premieres 'Ease My Mind' Music Video: WATCH|website=PEOPLE.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Theatre credits==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Production\n! Role\n! Venue\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2002\n| ''[[The Music Man]]''\n| Winthrop Paroo\n| [[Hollywood Bowl]]\n| Los Angeles\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Mame (musical)|Mame]]''\n| Patrick Denis\n| [[Hollywood Bowl]]\n| Los Angeles\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''[[Caroline, or Change]]''\n| Noah Gellman\n| [[Ahmanson Theatre]]\n| National tour\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Dead End (play)|Dead End]]''\n| Philip Griswald\n| [[Ahmanson Theatre]]\n| Regional\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2012\n| ''The Power of Duff''\n| Ricky Duff\n| [[Vassar College|Powerhouse Theatre]]\n| Regional\n|-\n| ''The Black Suits''\n| Chris Thurser\n|[[Barrington Stage Company]]\n| Regional\n|-\n| 2012\u20132013\n| rowspan=\"2\"| ''[[The Book of Mormon (musical)|The Book of Mormon]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Elder Arnold Cunningham\n| [[PrivateBank Theatre]]\n| Chicago\n|-\n| 2014\u20132015\n| [[Eugene O'Neill Theatre]]\n| [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Dear Evan Hansen]]''\n| Evan Hansen\n| [[Arena Stage]]\n| Washington, D.C.\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[The Secret Garden (musical)|The Secret Garden]]'' \n| Dickon\n| [[David Geffen Hall]]\n| 25th anniversary concert\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2016\u20132017\n| rowspan=\"2\" | ''[[Dear Evan Hansen]]'' \n| rowspan=\"2\" | Evan Hansen\n| [[Second Stage Theatre]]\n| Off-Broadway\n|-\n| [[Music Box Theatre]]\n| Broadway\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Parade (musical)|Parade]]''\n|[[Leo Frank]]\n|\n|Workshop\n|}\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year \n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''[[Red Riding Hood (2006 film)|Red Riding Hood]]''\n| Boy Scout #1\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Pitch Perfect]]''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Benji Applebaum\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2015\n| ''[[Pitch Perfect 2]]''\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Ricki and the Flash]]''\n| Daniel\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Billy Lynn's Long Halftime Walk (film)|Billy Lynn's Long Halftime Walk]]''\n| Josh\n|\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[The Female Brain (film)|The Female Brain]]''\n| Joel\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2019\n| ''[[Run This Town (film)|Run This Town]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/damian-lewis-play-controversial-toronto-mayor-rob-ford-thriller-1101298|title=Damian Lewis to Play Controversial Ex-Toronto Mayor Rob Ford in Drama|work=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=May 4, 2018}}</ref>\n| Bram Shriver\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Drunk Parents]]''\n| Jason Johnson\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/joe-manganiello-alec-baldwin-salma-hayek-drunk-parents-1201681014/|title=Joe Manganiello Joins Alec Baldwin, Salma Hayek's Comedy 'Drunk Parents'|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=January 15, 2016|work=Variety|accessdate=March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Broken Diamonds]]''\n| Scott\n| Completed\n|-\n| TBA\n| ''[[Merrily We Roll Along (film)|Merrily We Roll Along]]''\n|Charley Kringas \n| Will be filmed over 20 years<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sneider |first1=Jeff |title=Exclusive: Richard Linklater, Ben Platt, Beanie Feldstein Team for Sondheim Musical |url=http://collider.com/richard-linklater-beanie-feldstein-movie/#boyhood |accessdate=30 August 2019 |work=Collider |date=29 August 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year \n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| {{dts|2017|10|05|format=y}}\n| ''[[Will & Grace]]''\n| Blake\n| Episode: \"Who's Your Daddy\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playbill.com/article/will-grace-a-millennial-watch-ben-platt-do-some-cross-generational-flirting-in-new-episode|title=Will & Grace & A Millennial: Watch Ben Platt Do Some Cross-Generational Flirting in New Episode | work=[[Playbill]] | access-date=October 6, 2017|date=October 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2019\u2013present\n| ''[[The Politician (TV series)|The Politician]]''\n| Payton Hobart\n| Lead role; 8 episodes. Also executive producer\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[The Kelly Clarkson Show]]''\n|Himself\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/VIDEO-Ben-Platt-And-Kelly-Clarkson-Sing-An-Original-Arrangement-of-Make-You-Feel-My-Love-20191015|title=VIDEO: Ben Platt And Kelly Clarkson Sing An Original Arrangement of 'Make You Feel My Love'|work=Broadway World|date=2019-10-15|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Songland]]''\n| Himself\n| Episode: \"Ben Platt\"\n|-\n|2020\n|''Untitled Ben Platt Netflix Concert Special''\n|Himself\n|<ref name=\"hollywoodreporter.com\"/>\n|}\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"[[Ben Platt (actor)]]\n|- \n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:17em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"4\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br/><ref name=\"US200\">Peaks on the US Billboard 200:\n* For all except noted: {{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/ben-platt/chart-history/billboard-200|title=Ben Platt Chart History: Billboard 200|work=Billboard|accessdate=March 9, 2019}}\n* For ''Dear Evan Hansen (Original Broadway Cast Record